gh American and Chinese New Women emphasized individual autonomy in that each sought to act as historical agents for modern progress, their notions of subjectivity were in different ways linked to the ideologies of historical progress of their nations. Sasaki’s transnational history of these New Women explores the intersections of gender, modernity, and national identity within the politics of world history, where the nation-state increased its presence as a universal unit in an ever-interconnecting global context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMissions, AmericanzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen college teacherszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen missionarieszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 4aGender Studies. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170628840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501706288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501706288/original  a978-3-11-064982-6  Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016